This exercise teach to create packages:

A package is a folder with a file named __init__.py to define which module to export.
Each file *.py inside the folder  is a module

```python
# __init__.py 
from .count_in_list import count_in_list
from .fraction_of_list import fraction_of_list

``

a pyproject.toml file is required by tools such as pip, build or a setuptools 
to made the package installable.

The guide to construct the pyproject.toml is in 
https://packaging.python.org/en/latest/guides/writing-pyproject-toml/

barebone sections are:


"pip install ." builds and installs
"python -m build" builds two files in a "dist/" folder

Run this commands from pyproject.toml's folder


dist/
    my_package-0.0.1.tar.gz        # source distribution (sdist)
    my_package-0.0.1-py3-none-any.whl  # wheel (built distribution)

For development, use editable mode:
pip install -e .
The -e flag means any changes you make to your source code take effect immediately without reinstalling. Very useful while developing.

"python -m build" builds two files in a "dist/" folder

Run this commands from pyproject.toml's folder


dist/
    my_package-0.0.1.tar.gz        # source distribution (sdist)
    my_package-0.0.1-py3-none-any.whl  # wheel (built distribution)


pip install .dist/my_package-0.0.1-py3-none-any.whl

installs it in the venv. pip list will show it

There's also TestPyPI (test.pypi.org) for testing uploads before publishing for real:
twine upload --repository testpypi dist/*

then any boy can install from there
pip install --index-url https://test.pypi.org/simple/ your_package_name
